<paragraph id="D60CA2312E5CFF886CADF8CE03C50D98" blockId="1.[151,672,1907,1934]" box="[151,672,1907,1934]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">
<heading id="8D44155D2E5CFF886CADF8CE03C50D98" bold="true" box="[151,672,1907,1934]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" reason="1">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5CFF886CADF8CE03C50D98" bold="true" box="[151,672,1907,1934]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5CFF886CADF8CE004A0D98" authorityName="Jordal" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,303,1907,1934]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5CFF886CADF8CE004A0D98" bold="true" box="[151,303,1907,1934]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Diplotrichus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
phylogeny and biogeography
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D60CA2312E5CFF8B6CADF801052A0B57" blockId="1.[151,1437,1980,2043]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,825]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="103" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">
The maximum likelihood analysis of the concatenated gene sequences resulted in a tree topology with 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5CFF886935F80100EF0DED" authority="(Schedl, 1950)" baseAuthorityName="Schedl" baseAuthorityYear="1950" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5CFF886935F80101BF0DEC" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Diplotrichus minor</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="B222DFC02E5CFF886CD1F85D00E40DED" author="Schedl, K. E." box="[235,385,2016,2043]" pageId="1" pageNumber="102" pagination="105 - 111" refId="ref13069" refString="Schedl, K. E. (1950) Fauna Madagascariensis, I. Institut Scientifique de Madagascar, Memoires, Series A, 4, 105 - 111." type="journal article" year="1950">Schedl, 1950</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
as sister to the remaining species in the genus (
<figureCitation id="4E88BEB42E5CFF886F8BF85D02920DED" box="[945,1015,2016,2043]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[321,1265,836,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-198@5.[321,1265,833,1839]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 7. Maximum likelihood tree topology for Diplotrichus based on nucleotides from five gene fragments. Node support values from 100 bootstrap replicates are shown on branches." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5540564" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5540564/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="102">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). This species is the only one with a dorsal spike on the female scapus. Species with a faint to strong apical expansion of the elytra formed the next group consisting of 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5FFF8B6D17FF0603770AC2" authority="Jordal, 2021" authorityName="Jordal" authorityYear="2021" box="[301,530,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutior" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5FFF8B6D17FF0603770AC2" box="[301,530,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Diplotrichus acutior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="FFF4C3582E5FFF8B6E22FF06030A0AC3" box="[536,623,187,213]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5FFF8B6E99FF0602F50AC3" authority="Jordal, 2021" authorityName="Jordal" authorityYear="2021" box="[675,912,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falcatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5FFF8B6E99FF0602F50AC3" box="[675,912,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Diplotrichus falcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="FFF4C3582E5FFF8B6FADFF0602880AC3" box="[919,1005,187,213]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
These were sister to a clade consisting of two equally well supported groups. One group contained all South African species, including the 
<typeStatus id="09081C932E5FFF8B6928FF6204270AEF" box="[1298,1346,223,249]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5FFF8B6CADFEBE03500B0B" authority="(Schedl, 1958)" baseAuthorityName="Schedl" baseAuthorityYear="1958" box="[151,565,258,285]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5FFF8B6CADFEBE00E60B0B" box="[151,387,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Diplotrichus gracilis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="B222DFC02E5FFF8B6DA9FEBE03490B0B" author="Schedl, K. E." box="[403,556,258,285]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" pagination="557 - 560" refId="ref13129" refString="Schedl, K. E. (1958) A few new African Scolytidae in the British Museum. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 13, 557 - 560. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222935808650982" type="journal article" year="1958">Schedl, 1958</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The other group contained only Malagasy species such as 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5FFF8B68E1FEBE00EA0B57" authority="(Schedl, 1953)" baseAuthorityName="Schedl" baseAuthorityYear="1953" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catenatus">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5FFF8B68E1FEBE01850B56" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Diplotrichus catenatus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="B222DFC02E5FFF8B6CD5FE9A00E20B57" author="Schedl, K. E." box="[239,391,294,321]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" pagination="67 - 106" refId="ref13099" refString="Schedl, K. E. (1953) Fauna Madagascariensis, III. Institut Scientifique de Madagascar, Memoires, Series E, 8, 67 - 106." type="journal article" year="1953">Schedl, 1953</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Relationships within these two clades received lower support.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9EA9F1BA2E5FFF8B6CFDFEF605BE092F" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" type="description">
<paragraph id="D60CA2312E5FFF8B6CFDFEF600940BC7" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,825]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">
Analyses of individual genes revealed fairly similar results, varying in the position of 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5FFF8B68B4FEF604640B72" authorityName="Jordal" authorityYear="2021" box="[1166,1281,331,356]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutior">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5FFF8B68B4FEF604640B72" box="[1166,1281,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">D. acutior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5FFF8B6902FEF601DD0B9E" authorityName="Jordal" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falcatus">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5FFF8B6902FEF601DD0B9E" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">D. falcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Occasionally, these two species formed either a grade separating 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5FFF8B6F95FED205730B9E" baseAuthorityName="Schedl" baseAuthorityYear="1950" box="[943,1046,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5FFF8B6F95FED205730B9E" box="[943,1046,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">D. minor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the remaining taxa or formed the sister group to the South African species. In all cases the South African species were deeply nested within an assembly of Malagasy species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D60CA2312E5FFF8B6CFDFE6605BE092F" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,825]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">
The phylogenetic analysis adds additional evidence to a Malagasy origin of South African 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5FFF8B68EEFE6604070BE3" authorityName="Jordal" authorityYear="2021" box="[1236,1378,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5FFF8B68EEFE6604070BE3" box="[1236,1378,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Diplotrichus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The South African taxa that were analysed with molecular data are morphologically fairly similar to each other (
<figureCitation id="4E88BEB42E5FFF8B6972FE4201D1082B" captionStart-0="FIGURES 8–14" captionStart-1="FIGURES 15–24" captionStartId-0="6.[151,264,1442,1466]" captionStartId-1="8.[151,264,1852,1876]" captionTargetBox-0="[200,1410,259,1418]" captionTargetBox-1="[170,1434,229,1827]" captionTargetId-0="figure-22@6.[178,1410,181,1418]" captionTargetId-1="figure-22@8.[153,1434,181,1828]" captionTargetPageId-0="6" captionTargetPageId-1="8" captionText-0="FIGURES 8–14. Dorsal, lateral, and front view of Diplotrichus gracilis female (8, 10, 12) and male (13), and Diplotrichus widdringtoniae paratype (9, 11, 14)." captionText-1="FIGURES 15–24. Dorsal, lateral, and front view of Diplotrichus pilifrons sp. nov. female holotype (15, 18, 21) and male allotype frons (22), Diplotrichus calvifrons sp. nov. female holotype (16, 19, 23), and Diplotrichus medius sp. nov. female holotype (17, 20, 24)." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5540566" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5540568" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5540566/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5540568/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Figs 8– 24</figureCitation>
) and this clade was nested deeply within a grade of Malagasy species. This clearly documents a case of overseas dispersal in the direction from 
<collectingCountry id="AEA4E2A12E5FFF8B6DD1FDFA03170877" box="[491,626,583,609]" name="Madagascar" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="AEA4E2A12E5FFF8B6EAFFDFA02430877" box="[661,806,583,609]" name="South Africa" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">South Africa</collectingCountry>
. The timing of this event cannot be dated precisely given the large difference between stem and crown age for the South African clade. A new Beast analysis with 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5FFF8B6913FDD604F90892" authorityName="Jordal" authorityYear="2021" box="[1321,1436,619,644]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutior">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5FFF8B6913FDD604F90892" box="[1321,1436,619,644]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">D. acutior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="11B3D9B22E5FFF8B6CFDFD32002608BF" authorityName="Jordal" authorityYear="2021" box="[199,323,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Diplotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falcatus">
<emphasis id="E4C77E232E5FFF8B6CFDFD32002608BF" box="[199,323,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">D. falcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
added to the data matrix provided estimates similar to 
<bibRefCitation id="B222DFC02E5FFF8B6F88FD32053C08BC" author="Jordal, B. H." box="[946,1113,655,682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" pagination="245 - 278" refId="ref12908" refString="Jordal, B. H. (2021 b) A phylogenetic and taxonomic assessment of Afrotropical Micracidini (Coleoptera, Scolytinae) reveals a strong diversifying role for Madagascar. Organisms Diversity &amp; Evolution, 21, 245 - 278. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 13127 - 021 - 00481 - 4" type="journal article" year="2021">Jordal (2021b)</bibRefCitation>
, in the range from 29 (stem) to 14.5 (crown) Ma for the South African clade. This estimate extends over both sides in the Oligocene–Miocene transition; the Miocene recolonisation (of Africa) hypothesis is therefore only partly supported. Irrespective of the exact timing and process of the South African diversification, this genus provides yet another piece of evidence for Madagascar’s important historical role in fostering additional diversity in the Afrotropical region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
